{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c6470351-9e5c-4448-b155-6be00f7474a2","content":"There's no documentation on this topic in the current repository, but I can answer from general knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump` (NativeAOT):**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n   mkdir -p /tmp/cores\n   ```\n\n2. **Reproduce the crash.** macOS writes the core file to the configured path (e.g., `/tmp/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n3. **If macOS ReportCrash captured it instead**, check:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` / `.crash` files contain stack traces and register state.\n\n4. **Analyze the core with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/cores/core.12345 /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **Useful `lldb` commands:**\n   - `bt` — backtrace\n   - `bt all` — all threads\n   - `register read` — register state\n   - `image list` — loaded modules\n\n**Key notes:**\n- NativeAOT apps don't bundle `createdump`; macOS's native core dump mechanism is the fallback.\n- On Apple Silicon, you may need to disable SIP or adjust entitlements for core dumps to be written.\n- The `.crash` reports in `DiagnosticReports` are often sufficient for initial triage without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2ba83fa6-605c-40c0-b49a-68bc48091c44","outputTokens":392,"requestId":"D811:283A56:353599E:3A3C180:69FBF0E7"},"id":"163eeb6b-1cb0-4074-8ff6-edd04a8a41d9","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:54:56.947Z","parentId":"ea3abcb2-63a5-48cf-813b-e7cf7c82b7b7"}
